{"award_age":79.0,"bio_image":"full\/a77e374db826d9462131cb500fcc49c6a00a6303.jpg","category":"Physics","country":"United States","date_of_birth":"1930-05-10T00:00:00.000Z","date_of_death":null,"gender":"male","image_urls":["http:\/\/upload.wikimedia.org\/wikipedia\/commons\/thumb\/c\/c5\/Nobel_Prize_2009-Press_Conference_KVA-27.jpg\/220px-Nobel_Prize_2009-Press_Conference_KVA-27.jpg"],"link":"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/George_E._Smith","mini_bio":"<p><b>George Elwood Smith<\/b> (born May 10, 1930) is an American scientist, applied <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Physicist\" title=\"Physicist\">physicist<\/a>, and co-inventor of the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Charge-coupled_device\" title=\"Charge-coupled device\">charge-coupled device<\/a> (CCD). He was awarded a one-quarter share in the 2009 <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Nobel_Prize_in_Physics\" title=\"Nobel Prize in Physics\">Nobel Prize in Physics<\/a> for \"the invention of an imaging semiconductor circuit\u2014the CCD sensor, which has become an electronic eye in almost all areas of photography\".<sup id=\"cite_ref-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/George_E._Smith#cite_note-1\"><span>[<\/span>1<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup><\/p><p>Smith was born in <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/White_Plains,_New_York\" title=\"White Plains, New York\">White Plains<\/a>, <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/New_York\" title=\"New York\">New York<\/a>. Smith served in the US Navy, attained his BSc at the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/University_of_Pennsylvania\" title=\"University of Pennsylvania\">University of Pennsylvania<\/a> in 1955 and his PhD from the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/University_of_Chicago\" title=\"University of Chicago\">University of Chicago<\/a> in 1959 with a dissertation of only eight pages.<sup id=\"cite_ref-proquest_2-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/George_E._Smith#cite_note-proquest-2\"><span>[<\/span>2<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup> He worked at <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Bell_Labs\" title=\"Bell Labs\">Bell Labs<\/a> in <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Murray_Hill,_New_Jersey\" title=\"Murray Hill, New Jersey\">Murray Hill, New Jersey<\/a> from 1959 to his retirement in 1986, where he led research into novel lasers and semiconductor devices. During his tenure, Smith was awarded dozens of patents and eventually headed the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/VLSI\" title=\"VLSI\" class=\"mw-redirect\">VLSI<\/a> device department.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Earthtimes_3-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/George_E._Smith#cite_note-Earthtimes-3\"><span>[<\/span>3<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup><\/p><p>In 1969, Smith and <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Willard_Boyle\" title=\"Willard Boyle\">Willard Boyle<\/a> invented the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Charge-Coupled_Device\" title=\"Charge-Coupled Device\" class=\"mw-redirect\">Charge-Coupled Device<\/a> (CCD),<sup id=\"cite_ref-Nobelpressrelease_4-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/George_E._Smith#cite_note-Nobelpressrelease-4\"><span>[<\/span>4<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup> for which they have jointly received the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Franklin_Institute\" title=\"Franklin Institute\">Franklin Institute<\/a>'s <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Stuart_Ballantine_Medal\" title=\"Stuart Ballantine Medal\">Stuart Ballantine Medal<\/a> in 1973, the 1974 <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/IEEE_Morris_N._Liebmann_Memorial_Award\" title=\"IEEE Morris N. Liebmann Memorial Award\">IEEE Morris N. Liebmann Memorial Award<\/a>, the 2006 <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Charles_Stark_Draper_Prize\" title=\"Charles Stark Draper Prize\">Charles Stark Draper Prize<\/a>, and the 2009 <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Nobel_Prize_in_Physics\" title=\"Nobel Prize in Physics\">Nobel Prize in Physics<\/a>.<\/p><p>Both Boyle and Smith were avid sailors who took many trips together. After retirement Smith sailed around the world with his life partner, Janet, for seventeen years, eventually giving up his hobby in 2003 to \"spare his 'creaky bones' from further storms.\"<sup id=\"cite_ref-Earthtimes_3-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/George_E._Smith#cite_note-Earthtimes-3\"><span>[<\/span>3<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup> He currently resides in the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Waretown,_New_Jersey\" title=\"Waretown, New Jersey\">Waretown<\/a> section of <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Ocean_Township,_Ocean_County,_New_Jersey\" title=\"Ocean Township, Ocean County, New Jersey\">Ocean Township, Ocean County, New Jersey<\/a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-5\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/George_E._Smith#cite_note-5\"><span>[<\/span>5<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup><\/p>","name":"George E. Smith","place_of_birth":"White Plains, New York","place_of_death":null,"text":"George E. Smith , Physics, 2009","year":2009.0}